<br>
I'm 30. I have two kids. I've never hit either of them.<br>
<br>
But if they ever do something this fecked up, guess what? It'll be my fault.<br>
<br>
Parenting holds the same responsibility as, for instance, being a commanding officer in the military. If I am a Company Commander and one of my soldiers wanders off and does something horribly stupid like driving over a fellow soldier with a tank, it's my fault. Why is it my fault? Because I should've trained the first soldier to drive better and the second to get the heck outta the way.<br>
<br>
The same holds true for parenting. If my daughter gets one of my handguns and blows away one of her friends, it's my goddam fault. Why? Because I should've taught her not to play with guns and because I should've secured my firearms better.<br>
<br>
Legally speaking, children are chattel. Look it up. Chattel equals baggage, goods, possessions, whatever. You are responsible for the damage if your car springs a gas leak and sets your neighbour's house on fire. You are responsible if a tree on your property falls onto someone else's fence and destroys it. You are responsible for the damage if your dog bites someone. You are equally responsible if your child throws a rock through a window or blows away someone else's child in fit of teen angst.<br>
<br>
See, just because you cannot thoroughly stop your 17 year old video-gameplaying, Marilyn-Manson-loving wannabe-ghetto-rat from whacking his buddy one afternoon doesn't absolve you from blame. That wannabe-ghetto-rat is your fault. You brought it into the world. You inflicted it upon the world. It's your fault until it is legally its' own person, ie the age of Majority.<br>
<br>
It's the parent's fault. If you can't see that, make sure you don't produce any offspring of your own.<br>
<br>
Being a parent is too damn big a job for a pinhead.   <p>a_Bearhat01<BR>
